arch:property.oc:show_val: X3 is a bone point. Flot sample 2 (4170), >4 mm, 100% sorted, only diagnostics A medium-sized unit of generally light to light-medium brown bone. The fragment size is comparatively large with very little trampling or abrasion. There is a small amount of low temperature burning in the dry sieve. There is some digestion and gnawing, but less than in many of the other west mound units. There are a number of fragile epiphyses, some with their unfused shafts and F113 to F117 are 6 caprine carpals that are from the same individual, and were probably articulated in the ground. There are also 4 pairs of articulated sheep phalanges. The fragment size is larger than in fill, with several pieces over 5 cm and there is one complete caprine metatarsal and a large part of a red deer metatarsal. In fact the bag of identified bones is larger than the bag of scrap - even without the red deer metapodial. The red deer metatarsal appears to be a preform and the caprine metatarsal may have also been intended for use. There are a lot of very small end splinters from other caprine metapodials that appear to have been deliberately smashed - since the other evidence does not suggest bone grease production or post-depositional factors perhaps this was part of tool production - it is certain that the metapodials were more highly processed than the other bones. There is one bone point that was identified in the fill and given an X number. One large sheep distal femur was also X-numbered for uncertain reasons (X9). Caprines are, as usual, overwhelmingly predominant but there are also one red deer metatarsal, a cattle atlas and phalanx, a human toe bone and one dog tooth. All elements of the caprine skeleton are represented including limbs, girdle, skull and feet and teeth but the foot bones are much more common than the other elements. The majority of the caprine bones are juvenile. Where they can be separated all the caprine bones are sheep. Overall the material looks like a primary deposit of material from mixed household activities including, butchery, consumption and tool making and perhaps curation of bones for use in tool making. it is reminiscent of the courtyard middens of the east mound. The material was definitely rapidly buried and there is very little disturbance - the human toe may have come from a nearby burial via a ground squirrel burrow, but most of the deposit is intact. One of the sheep astragalus has butchery-related cut marks on it. This is common in prehistoric sites, but is very rare on the east mound. if there are more cut marks in other units it may indicate a change in butchery practices. The flot sample was about 10 burnt, generally light to medium brown. Edges were generally sharp and there was very little abrasion or polish. The only diagnostics were sheep/goat. NR 2006: H2 was returned from the figurines; it is in fact the base of an abraded metapodial point. Last Number = 145
